[2/10] P5 English EOY Nanyang 2025 — Q2  Primary 5  (12.7s)
============================================================
STEM: Rachel has a small appetite, so she ordered a dish without ___ meat.
  (1) less
  (2) little
  (3) many
  (4) much
ANSWER: 4

ELABORATION (672 chars):
This question tests **quantifiers with uncountable nouns**.

The word "meat" is an **uncountable noun**. We use "**much**" in negative contexts (like after the word "without") to mean a large amount, so ordering a dish "without **much** meat" is perfect for someone with a small appetite!

Here is why the other options are incorrect:
**(1)** "less" is a **comparative quantifier** used to compare two things, which is not happening here.
**(2)** "little" creates an illogical meaning, because "without **little** meat" actually implies she wants a lot of meat!
**(3)** "many" is a **quantifier** only used with **countable nouns** (like "apples" or "plates"), not "meat".

